///

/// Scope

@node Scope
@title "The Scope"

The Scope

The scope of LogicSim can have unlimited number of channels.

To use the scope you have to place the probes to the gates
you want to scope. Do this with the function @{"New channel" link NEWCHANNEL}.


The scope can't be showed while simulating, so you have to
record the scope and display it after simulation.

@{"Start" link START} the simulation and select @{"Record" link RECORD} from
the Scope menu. "Scope active" is shown in the window title and the scope is
recording.
To stop the recording select @{"Stop record" link STOPRECORD} from the scope menu.
It is also stopped when you abort the simulation.

You can also start and stop the recording by the two special gates
@{"Scope Start" link GATE_SCOPESTART} and @{"Scope Stop" link GATE_SCOPESTOP}.
See the example circuit "Scope".


Now, you can display the scope with the menu item @{"Show scope" link SHOWSCOPE}.
You can scale the scope with the scale gadget.

You can save the scope graphics with the menu item "Save iff ...".


@endnode

///


Menus


/// NEW

@node NEW
@title "New"

Delete the old circuit and begin a new one.

You will be asked to save the circuit first.


@endnode

///

/// LOAD

@node LOAD
@title "Load"

Load a circuit from disk.
The old circuit will be deleted.

You will be asked to save the old circuit first.


If the size of the loaded circuit is greater than your
current @{"work area" link WORKAREA} size, the wor area
size will be increased.


@endnode

///

/// SAVE

@node SAVE
@title "Save"

Save a circuit to disk.

If no filename was given before, a filerequester will be opened.


@endnode

///

/// SAVEAS

@node SAVEAS
@title "Save as"

This equals the @{"Save" link SAVE} menu, but you will be
asked for a filename first.


@endnode

///

/// SAVEIFF

@node SAVEIFF
@title "Save iff"


This allows you to save your circuit as IFF-ILBM picture.

The circuit is saved as uncompressed ILBM. I hope all programs
are able to load this.

@endnode

///

/// PRINT

@node PRINT
@title "Print"

This allows you to print your circuit.

You will be asked to open the GfxPrefs-Editor.
You can also print an additional @{"Comment" link COMMENT}.


@endnode

///

/// COMMENT

@node COMMENT
@title "Comment"

You can enter an additional comment, author and date to your
circuit. This comment can be printed with the circuit.


@endnode

///

/// ABOUT

@node ABOUT
@title "About"

This shows some information about the program.


If you have OS3.0+ and at least 32 colors, a picture
is shown in the about requester. The picture is stored
in LSAboutPic. If you have no OS3, not enough colors or
LogicSim can't find the picture file, an internal picture
is shown.


@endnode

///

/// REDRAW

@node REDRAW
@title "Redraw"

This refreshes the circuit graphics.
Not really needed, but I used it while developing.

@endnode

///

/// QUIT

@node QUIT
@title "Quit"

This item leaves the program.

You will be asked to save the circuit first.

@endnode

///

/// MOVECIRC

@node MOVECIRC
@title "Move circuit"

You can move the circuit in the work area.

A frame is drawn around the circuit while moving it.
You can move this frame to the new position and press
the left mouse button. The circuit will be moved to the
new position.

@endnode

///

/// CONNECT

@node CONNECT
@title "Connect"

Shortcut: c

Connect a output of a gate or a node with the
input of a gate.

First you have to click on a output of gate or on
a node. Then you can draw a wire to an input of a
gate. By pressing SPACE you can add a node to the
last position of the wire, by pressing 'u' you can
remove the last drawn part of the wire.

You can exit the connect mode by pressing ESC or selecting
an other menu item.


@endnode

///

/// ADDNODE

@node ADDNODE
@title "Add node"



You can add a node to a previous drawn wire.

Click on the wire where you want to add the node.
If you click near to an edge, the node will be added to this edge.


@endnode

///

/// REMOVENODE

@node REMOVENODE
@title "Remove node"


You can remove a node from a wire by clicking on the
node to delete.


@endnode

///

/// REMOVEGATE

@node REMOVEGATE
@title "Remove gate"

Shortcut: d


You can remove a gate from your circuit by calling this
function and clicking on the gate to remove.

All wires connected to the removed gate will also be removed.


You can undo this action by pressing 'u' or the 'undo' button.


@endnode

///

/// REMOVEWIRE

@node REMOVEWIRE
@title "Remove wire"

Shortcut: w


You can remove a wire from your circuit by calling this
function and clicking on the wire to remove.

You can undo this action by pressing 'u' or the 'undo' button.


@endnode

///

/// UNDO

@node UNDO
@title "Undo"


Shortcut: u


With the UNDO function you can undo the last action
(remove gate, remove wire...).

Using UNDO again will redo the action.




In future versions of LogicSim I'll make more undo-steps.


@endnode

///

/// LABEL

@node LABEL
@title "Label"


This menu item starts the label mode.

In this mode you can click on a gate to open the
@{"label-requester" link LABELREQUESTER}.

In this requester you can input a text, select its
position and select a font for the text.

After this the gate will be labeled with your text.



You can exit the label mode by pressing the ESC-key.


@endnode

///

/// COPY

@node COPY
@title "Copy"


You can copy a part of your circuit to @{"insert" link INSERT} it later
at another position or in a new circuit.
This function is similar to to the copy function in text editors.

All wires which are with beginning and end in the area you selected
will be copied, too.



@endnode

///

/// CUT

@node CUT
@title "Cut"


This function is similar to the @{"copy" link COPY} function, but
all copied gates and wires are removed from your circuit afterwards.

@endnode

///

/// START

@node START
@title "Start"

This will start the simulation of your circuit.

You can pause the simulation with @{"Pause" link PAUSE}.
The simulation can be stopped with ESC or @{"Stop" link STOP}.

Select the @{"hightlight HIGH wire" link HIGHLIGHT} menu, if you want
to 'debug' your circuit.


@endnode

///

/// STOP

@node STOP
@title "Stop"

This will exit the simulation mode. It is the same as pressing
the ESC key while simulating.


@endnode

///

/// PAUSE

@node PAUSE
@title "Pause"

Whit this menu item, you can halt your simulation in the current
state. To run it again, turn this menu item off.

You can also use this menu item before starting the simulation
with @{"Start" link START}. NOTHING will be simulated, when you start
the simulation in that case, until you turn the pause-item off.



@endnode

///

/// HIGHLIGHT

@node HIGHLIGHT
@title "highlight HIGH wire"


When using this function, all wires with HIGH will be drawn
white in simulation mode.
This is useful if you want to 'debug' your circuit.

This menu-item must be turned on/off BEFORE starting the
simulation mode.


@endnode

///

/// NEWCHANNEL

@node NEWCHANNEL
@title "New channel"

New channel for the @{"Scope" link SCOPE}.

You have to place the probe to an output of a gate or a node.

@endnode

///

/// REMOVECHAN

@node REMOVECHAN
@title "Remove channel"

Remove an channel of the @{"Scope" link SCOPE}.

You have to input the number of the probe/channel to remove.

@endnode

///

/// REMALLCHAN

@node REMALLCHAN
@title "Remove all channels"

Remove ALL channels of the @{"Scope" link SCOPE}.

See @{"Remove channel" link REMOVECHAN}.

@endnode

///

/// RECORD

@node RECORD
@title "Record"

Start the record of scope data.

See @{"Scope" link SCOPE}

@endnode

///

/// STOPRECORD

@node STOPRECORD
@title "Stop record"

Stop the record of scope data.

See @{"Scope" link SCOPE}


@endnode

///

/// SHOWSCOPE

@node SHOWSCOPE
@title "Show Scope"

Open the @{"Scope" link SCOPE} window.

@endnode

///

/// INSERT

@node INSERT
@title "Insert"


With this function you can insert a previously @{"copied" link COPY} or @{"cutted" link CUT}
part of a circuit in your actual circuit.

@endnode

///

/// SCREENMODE

@node SCREENMODE
@title "ScreenMode"


You can select a ScreenMode in the ASL/ReqTools ScreenMode-Requester,
LogicSim will run on.

Pressing the OK button in the requester will open a screen in the
selected mode. You can move LogicSim back on the Workbench Screen
by turning the menu @{"use workbench" link USEWB} on.

@endnode

///

/// WORKAREA

@node WORKAREA
@title "work area"

You can select the width and height of the work area (the area
where you draw your circuits, it can be scrolled around).

Note: Big sizes will need *MUCH* chip-memory.
      You can calclulate the chip-mem needed by mem=width*height/4.
      If you set values which are bigger than your free chip-mem,
      the size will be decreased.


@endnode

///

/// USEWB

@node USEWB
@title "use workbench"


The display mode of LogicSim is changed from custom screen to
Workbench screen and back.

@endnode

///

/// GRID

@node GRID
@title "Show grid"

    Turn the grid on/off.

    You need a fast CPU for the grid !

@endnode

///

/// EWINOPEN

@node EWINOPEN
@title "Edit window open"

If you have closed the edit-window (-> @{"Windows" link GADGETS}), you can
reopen it with this menu.


@endnode

///

/// SAVEWITHICON

@node SAVEWITHICON
@title "Save with icon"

This lets LogicSim save your circuits with additional icons.

When you click these icons on workbench, LogicSim will
be started and loads the circuit.

@endnode

///

/// SAVESET

@node SAVESET
@title "Save settings"

This will save your settings and window positions
in the file LogicSim.config.


@endnode

///

/// HELP

@node HELP
@title "Help"

This tells you that the program has an online help system,
if you don't know it. :-)

@endnode

///

/// CONTENTS

@node CONTENTS
@title "Contents"

This loads the contents page of this AmigaGuide document.

@endnode

///


Gates


/// GATE_xInputs

@node GATE_xInputs
@title "Number of Inputs"


Shortcut: 2, 3, 5

Here you can set the number of inputs for @{"AND" link GATE_AND}, @{"NAND" link GATE_NAND},
@{"OR" link GATE_OR}, @{"NOR" link GATE_NOR}, and @{"XOR" link GATE_XOR} gates.

Possible numbers of inputs are 2, 3 and 5.

@endnode

///

/// GATE_SWITCH

@node GATE_SWITCH
@title "Switch"


Switch

Shortcut: s

This is an element for user inputs.

It can be used as switch or key. If you use it as switch,
you can click on it (in simulation mode) to turn it on
(output=HIGH) and click again to turn it off (output=LOW).
If you use it as key, clicking on it turns it on and releasing
the button after this turns it off.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/Switch.iff"}


Click on the gate to open the @{"switch requester" link SWITCHREQUESTER}.


@endnode

///

/// GATE_LED

@node GATE_LED
@title "LED"


LED

Shortcut: l


This is an output element, it is colored if HIGH and
transparent if LOW.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/LED.iff"}



@endnode

///

/// GATE_AND

@node GATE_AND
@title "AND"


AND

Shortcut: a


The output is only HIGH when ALL inputs are HIGH.


You can choose the number of inputs (2, 3 or 5) in the
menu or the "basic gates"-window.

Click on the gate to replace it with @{"NAND" link GATE_NAND}, @{"OR" link GATE_OR}, @{"NOR" link GATE_NOR}, @{"XOR" link GATE_XOR}.



      A | B | Q
     ---+---+---
      0 | 0 | 0         A - input 1
      0 | 1 | 0         B - input 2
      1 | 0 | 0         Q - output
      1 | 1 | 1


   @{" Show Gate    " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/AND.iff"}
   @{" Show diagram " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/AND_diagram.iff"}



   ^
  A|
   |     ____      ____
   |    |    |    |    |
   |    |    |    |    |
   |____|    |____|    |____
   +-------------------------------->
                                   t

   ^
  B|
   |          _________
   |         |         |
   |         |         |
   |_________|         |____
   +-------------------------------->
                                   t

   ^
  Q|
   |               ____
   |              |    |
   |              |    |
   |______________|    |____
   +-------------------------------->
                                   t


@endnode

///

/// GATE_NAND

@node GATE_NAND
@title "NAND"


NAND

Shortcut: A


This is an @{"AND" link GATE_AND} with inverted output


You can choose the number of inputs (2, 3 or 5) in the
menu or the "basic gates"-window.

Click on the gate to replace it with @{"AND" link GATE_AND}, @{"OR" link GATE_OR}, @{"NOR" link GATE_NOR}, @{"XOR" link GATE_XOR}.



      A | B | Q
     ---+---+---
      0 | 0 | 1         A - input 1
      0 | 1 | 1         B - input 2
      1 | 0 | 1         Q - output
      1 | 1 | 0


   @{" Show Gate    " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/NAND.iff"}
   @{" Show diagram " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/NAND_diagram.iff"}



   ^
  A|
