///

/// GATE_TRAFFICLIGHT

@node GATE_TRAFFICLIGHT
@title "traffic light"


traffic light model



This is a model of a traffic light with red, yellow and green
lights.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/traffic_light.iff"}


Per default the color of each light is blue. Click on the
gate to open the @{"traffic light requester" link TRAFFICLIGHTREQUESTER} where
you can select the color for each light.


@endnode

///

/// GATE_NUMDISPLAY

@node GATE_NUMDISPLAY
@title "numeric display"


7 segment display model



This is an model of a 7 segment numeric display. It shows decimal
numbers from 0 to 31 or HEX numbers from $0 to $1F. It has 5 inputs
that represent the binaries 2^0 ... 2^4. If you only want number
up to 15 or 8, you should set the inputs 2^5, 2^4 ... to @{"LOW" link GATE_LOW}.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/numericdisplay.iff"}



Click on the gate to open a @{"requester" link NUMDISPLAYREQUESTER} where you can choose
between decimal and hexadecimal format.

@endnode

///

/// GATE_INPUTINV

@node GATE_INPUTINV
@title "input inverter"


input inverter


This is the same as the @{"NOT" link GATE_NOT} gate, but with
graphically differences.

This gate is placed directly to an input of a gate.
So the level on input is first inverted before it goes
to the input of the 'big' gate.

   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/inputinverter.iff"}



@endnode

///

/// GATE_LOW

@node GATE_LOW
@title "LOW"


LOW


This is to permanently set an input of a gate to LOW.
For example, if you need a OR with 4 inputs,
take one with 5 inputs and set one input to LOW.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/LOW.iff"}



@endnode

///

/// GATE_HIGH

@node GATE_HIGH
@title "HIGH"


HIGH



This is to permanently set an input of a gate
to HIGH. For example, if you need a AND with 4 inputs,
take one with 5 inputs and set one input to HIGH.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/HIGH.iff"}



@endnode

///

/// GATE_SCOPESTART

@node GATE_SCOPESTART
@title "Scope Start"

Scope Start

This starts the scope recording on the LOW-HIGH jump of the input.
It is the same as the menu item @{"Record" link RECORD}.

The scope is only started once, more LOW-HIGH jumps are ignored.

You can place only one of this gate.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/ScopeStart.iff"}


@endnode

///

/// GATE_SCOPESTOP

@node GATE_SCOPESTOP
@title "Scope Stop"

Scope Stop

This stops the scope recording on the LOW-HIGH jump of the input.
It is the same as the menu item @{"Stop Record" link STOPRECORD}.

You can place only one of this gate.


   @{" Show Gate " system "execute gfx/Show gfx/ScopeStop.iff"}


@endnode

///


Requesters


/// TimeRequester

@node TIMEREQUESTER
@title "Time Requester"


This is the requester to set the time values of @{"Clock" link GATE_CLOCK},
@{"Monoflop" link GATE_MONO}, @{"turn on delay" link GATE_TOND} and @{"turn off delay" link GATE_TOFFD}.

You can set the impulse and pause time for Clock and only one time
for the other gates.

All times are millisecond values.



You can set the initial level for Clock.
With set to HIGH the Clock pulse will start with HIGH, otherwise with LOW.



Note: Under OS2.0 the initial level gadgets are'nt disabled for gates other
      than Clock. Using this gadget won't effect anything in this case.


@endnode

///

/// SwitchRequester

@node SWITCHREQUESTER
@title "Switch Requester"


This requester appears when you click on a @{"switch" link GATE_SWITCH}.

You can set the color of the switch when it is on/HIGH, the initial level
and the type of the switch.


Per default a switch is turned off at start, with initial
level set to HIGH the switch is turned on at start and you
turn it off with first click.


With the type gadgets you can choose a real switch or
a key.
If you use it as switch, you can click on it (in simulation mode)
to turn it on (output=HIGH) and click again to turn it off (output=LOW).
If you use it as key, clicking on it turns it on and releasing
the button after this turns it off.



@endnode

///

/// LEDRequester

@node LEDREQUESTER
@title "LED Requester"


This requester appears when you click on a @{"LED" link GATE_LED}.


In this requester you can only set the color of the LED when it is on.


@endnode

///

/// TrafficLightRequester

@node TRAFFICLIGHTREQUESTER
@title "Traffic Light Requester"


This requester appears when you click on a @{"traffic light" link GATE_TRAFFICLIGHT}.


Here you can select the screen-color for each light (red, yellow, green).
Per default all colors are blue.

If you select "find best color", the program tries to allocate
colors that match red, yellow and green. This feature is only
available for OS3.0 and above.


You should use a worbench or custom screen with at least 8
colors for correct red, yellow and green color.


@endnode

///

/// NumDisplayRequester

@node NUMDISPLAYREQUESTER
@title "Numeric Display Requester"


This requester appears when you click on a @{"numeric display" link GATE_NUMDISPLAY}.


Here you can set the mode for display (hex or decimal).
You can also turn off the leading 0. For example, with leading 0 off
the number 7 is shown as " 7", not as "07".


@endnode

///

/// LabelRequester

@node LABELREQUESTER
@title "Label Requester"


In the string-gadget you can input the label-text with
max. 16 letters.

You can choose the text position above or below.

"Select font" opens a font requester where you can
select a font for the label text. This font is used
for ALL label texts, not just for this gate.
The default font is TinyTxt.font supplied in the
LogicSim archive.



@endnode

